The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent academic excellence service, and this continued in 2018 with a series of excellent exam results, and also individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other initiatives of the whole community.
With more than 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their pupils for continuing and higher education, the career they choose and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a custom-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desired subjects at the best of schools.
Nelson Mandela said: ‘If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
When you talk to him in his own language, you reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and a bond of trust with people from other countries.
From the recent exam results of this year, we can conclude that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
A total of 68% of the students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data collected from 74 schools joined SCIS shows that 72 percent of the students achieved a high score in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also achieved A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now rated as professional as STEM subjects (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in independent school programmes and elsewhere.
A study by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 revealed that 17% of the obstacles to job creation were attributed to a lack of language knowledge, according to employers.
Language skills thus become increasingly important to prepare young people for their future career.
Now that there is an increasing demand for language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if he has learned a second language, he has in the future a real advantage with such a skill for life.
Direct communication with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person a lead in competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation. French was the only language that exceeded 10 percent, with a total of 15%.
This is why investing in language education is now important for the children of today.
Several languages, in particular those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland schools themselves choose which languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the United Kingdom when they look forward to 2020, such as the Mandarin or Japan.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specializing in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that languages in a global business environment remain vitally important for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il faut been le faire.
