National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research carried out on an estate in the Scottish highlands is trying to reveal how bats make use of the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will light up the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to future conservation activities.
The study carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland follows the ordinary and the small dwarf bat, the brown large-eared bat and the waterwing mouse at Inverewe Gardens in Western Ross.
Special recording equipment shall be placed at key locations around the estate to follow the activities of bats throughout the season.
Staff members of the NTS and volunteers will also carry out mobile investigations using hand detectors.
Expert audio analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the calls of the bat and what kind of thing does.
A map of habitat and a report is then produced to give a detailed picture on the landscape scale of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation adviser to the NTS, hopes that the results show the habitat's most important areas for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as making meadows and how we can best maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities affecting dorms and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightnings can also pose a risk, as can flight fans and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not blind in reality.
Because of their night hunting habits, however, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo-location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight route.
At the NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts who conduct regular investigations, bedside inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even set up the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten species of bats of Scotland live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says that the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Thrave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much is not yet known about bats, and that's why the work we do here and in other locations will help us to understand better what they need in order to thrive."
It stresses the importance of monitoring bats before maintenance is carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a sleeping place can result in the death of 400 female bats and their offspring, thus potentially destroying a complete local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, to bother or to disturb them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, "We still have to learn a lot about our bats and many of our species, we simply don't know how their populations are doing."
