How the US-China trade war can be beneficial to Beijing
The opening balances of the US-China trade war were overwhelming, and although the fight has not been fought for a long time, a long-term gap between the two countries could be beneficial for Beijing, according to experts.
Donald Trump, the U.S. President, gave the first warning earlier this year by increasing taxes on major Chinese export products, including solar panels, steel and aluminium.
The most significant escalation became known this week when new effective, increased tax rates were revealed at $200 billion (€150 billion) of goods; half of all goods from China's US income.
Beijing has taken natural reprisals every time, most recently by increasing rates from 5 to 10% for 60 billion dollars in American goods.
China has committed to equalizing the US every time, and the world on a second-largest economy is probably not going to blink with its eyes fast.
In order to bend Washington, requests have to be granted, but public bending for the US is far too painful for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
However, experts claim that if Beijing plays smart, the trade war with the US, China could support it positively in the longer term, as the mutual dependence on the two economies decreases.
'The fact that a rapid political decision could create conditions in Washington or Beijing, which would enable one of the two countries to fall into an economic free trap, is really far more dangerous than spectators have previously recognized', says Abigail Grace, a research employee of the 'Center for a New American Security', a think tank specializing in national security issues, focusing on Asia.
Syria is 'ready' to allow refugees to return, according to Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country destroyed by a war that lasts more than seven years.
In his speech to the UN General Assembly, Minister for Foreign Affairs, Walid al-Moualem, stated that the conditions in his country improved.
"Today, the situation on the spot is more stable and safer, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism," he says.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists and normalize the situation on the ground.
All the circumstances are now present for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they have had to leave because of terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that threaten their daily life and existence.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have escaped their country since the war began in 2011.
It is estimated that some six million people live in the country who need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian regime would welcome help in restoring the destroyed country.
However, he stressed that Syria would not accept conditional assistance or assistance from countries that had subsidized the rebellion.
